  "prompt": "Why is a quadratic equation called 'quadratic', though it has a degree of two and quad means four (eg : x^2-2x-3)?",
  "response": "The term \"quadratic\" comes from the Latin word \"quadratus,\" which means \"square.\" This is because quadratic equations involve the squaring of the variable, which is represented by the term \\(x^2\\). The name relates not to the number four or having a degree of four, but rather to the squaring operation. In other words, a quadratic equation is one that involves the second power of the variable, and hence the term \"quadratic\" refers to the shape of a square in geometric terms, rather than the number four.",
